# Design Patterns — Factory Method & Abstract Factory

Recommendations for integrating **1 Factory Method** and **2 Abstract Factory** usages into the unimplemented use cases.

---

## 1. Factory Method Pattern — Transaction Creation (UC-05, UC-06, UC-07)

### Problem
Three use cases need to create [Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124) objects with different types:

| Use Case | Transaction Type | Controller |
|----------|-----------------|------------|
| UC-05 Deposit | [Deposit](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/DepositHandler.java#22-32) | [DepositHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/DepositHandler.java#9-64) |
| UC-06 Withdraw | [Withdrawal](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/WithdrawCashForm.java#48-56) | [WithdrawCashController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/WithdrawCashController.java#8-80) |
| UC-07 Transfer | `TransferDebit` / `TransferCredit` | [TransferHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/TransferHandler.java#6-53) |

Each controller currently has its own `record*Tx()` stub method that duplicates the same object-construction logic — building a [Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124), setting fields, and returning it. This is a classic case for **Factory Method**: define a creation interface in a base class, and let subclasses decide which type of [Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124) to create.

### Design

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class TransactionController {
        <<abstract>>
        +execute(String accountNo, double amount, String desc) int
        #validateAmount(double amount) boolean
        #getAccount(String accountNo) Account
        #createTransaction(String accountNo, double amount, String desc, double balanceAfter) Transaction*
        #recordTransaction(Transaction tx) int
    }

    class DepositHandler {
        +execute(String accountNo, double amount, String desc) int
        #createTransaction(...) Transaction
    }

    class WithdrawCashController {
        +execute(String accountNo, double amount, String desc) int
        #createTransaction(...) Transaction
        -checkSufficientFunds(String accountNo, double amount) boolean
    }

    class TransferHandler {
        +execute(...) int
        #createTransaction(...) Transaction
        -generateReferenceCode() String
    }

    TransactionController <|-- DepositHandler
    TransactionController <|-- WithdrawCashController
    TransactionController <|-- TransferHandler
    TransactionController ..> Transaction : creates
```

### How it works

1. **`TransactionController`** (new abstract class) provides the template:
   - `execute()` — orchestrates: validate → get account → compute new balance → `createTransaction()` → `recordTransaction()`
   - `createTransaction()` — **abstract factory method** — overridden by each subclass

2. **Each subclass overrides `createTransaction()`** to set the correct `type` field:

```java
// In DepositHandler
@Override
protected Transaction createTransaction(String accountNo, double amount,
                                         String desc, double balanceAfter) {
    Transaction tx = new Transaction();
    tx.setAccountNumber(accountNo);
    tx.setType("Deposit");           // <-- subclass decides the type
    tx.setAmount(BigDecimal.valueOf(amount));
    tx.setNote(desc);
    tx.setBalanceAfter(BigDecimal.valueOf(balanceAfter));
    tx.setTimestamp(LocalDateTime.now());
    return tx;
}

// In WithdrawCashController
@Override
protected Transaction createTransaction(...) {
    Transaction tx = new Transaction();
    tx.setType("Withdrawal");        // <-- different type
    // ... same structure, different type value
    return tx;
}
```

3. The existing [recordDepositTx()](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/DepositHandler.java#51-62) / [recordWithdrawalTx()](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/WithdrawCashController.java#67-78) stub methods are **replaced** by the inherited `recordTransaction()` + overridden `createTransaction()`.

### Files affected

| Action | File |
|--------|------|
| **[NEW]** | `domain/controller/TransactionController.java` — abstract base with factory method |
| **[MODIFY]** | [domain/controller/DepositHandler.java](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/DepositHandler.java) — extend `TransactionController`, override `createTransaction()` |
| **[MODIFY]** | [domain/controller/WithdrawCashController.java](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/WithdrawCashController.java) — extend `TransactionController`, override `createTransaction()` |
| **[MODIFY]** | [domain/controller/TransferHandler.java](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/TransferHandler.java) — extend `TransactionController`, override `createTransaction()` |

