## 2. Abstract Factory Pattern #1 — Loan Processing (UC-09, UC-10, UC-11)

### Problem
The three loan use cases share the same entity ([Loan](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Loan.java#8-69)) but need **different families of related objects** depending on the loan type (e.g. Personal, Home, Auto):

- **Validator** — different rules per loan type (max amount, allowed durations, required fields)
- **InterestCalculator** — different rate formulas per loan type
- **Loan entity** — pre-configured with type-specific defaults

These form a **family of related objects** that must be consistent — you can't mix a Personal loan validator with a Home loan interest calculator. This is the textbook case for **Abstract Factory**.

### Design

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class LoanFactory {
        <<interface>>
        +createValidator() LoanValidator
        +createInterestCalculator() LoanInterestCalculator
        +createLoan(int customerId, double amount, int months, String purpose) Loan
    }

    class PersonalLoanFactory {
        +createValidator() LoanValidator
        +createInterestCalculator() LoanInterestCalculator
        +createLoan(...) Loan
    }

    class HomeLoanFactory {
        +createValidator() LoanValidator
        +createInterestCalculator() LoanInterestCalculator
        +createLoan(...) Loan
    }

    class AutoLoanFactory {
        +createValidator() LoanValidator
        +createInterestCalculator() LoanInterestCalculator
        +createLoan(...) Loan
    }

    class LoanValidator {
        <<interface>>
        +validate(double amount, int months, String purpose) boolean
    }

    class LoanInterestCalculator {
        <<interface>>
        +calculateRate(double amount, int months) double
    }

    LoanFactory <|.. PersonalLoanFactory
    LoanFactory <|.. HomeLoanFactory
    LoanFactory <|.. AutoLoanFactory
    PersonalLoanFactory ..> LoanValidator : creates
    PersonalLoanFactory ..> LoanInterestCalculator : creates
    HomeLoanFactory ..> LoanValidator : creates
    HomeLoanFactory ..> LoanInterestCalculator : creates
```

### How it works

1. **`LoanFactory`** (new interface) declares 3 factory methods:
   - `createValidator()` → returns the appropriate `LoanValidator`
   - `createInterestCalculator()` → returns the appropriate `LoanInterestCalculator`
   - `createLoan(...)` → creates a pre-configured [Loan](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Loan.java#8-69) entity

2. **Concrete factories** (`PersonalLoanFactory`, `HomeLoanFactory`, `AutoLoanFactory`) each return a **consistent family**:
   - Personal: max $50K, max 60 months, rate ~15%
   - Home: max $500K, max 360 months, rate ~5%
   - Auto: max $100K, max 84 months, rate ~8%

3. **[LoanApplicationHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/LoanApplicationHandler.java#10-56)** uses the factory:

```java
public class LoanApplicationHandler {
    public Set<Loan> applyForLoan(int customerId, double amount,
                                   String loanType, int months, String purpose) {
        // Get the right factory for this loan type
        LoanFactory factory = getLoanFactory(loanType);

        // Use factory to get type-specific validator
        LoanValidator validator = factory.createValidator();
        if (!validator.validate(amount, months, purpose)) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Validation failed");
        }

        // Use factory to create the loan with correct defaults
        Loan loan = factory.createLoan(customerId, amount, months, purpose);

        // Use factory to calculate interest rate
        LoanInterestCalculator calc = factory.createInterestCalculator();
        double rate = calc.calculateRate(amount, months);
        // ... persist loan with rate ...
    }

    private LoanFactory getLoanFactory(String loanType) {
        return switch (loanType.toUpperCase()) {
            case "PERSONAL" -> new PersonalLoanFactory();
            case "HOME"     -> new HomeLoanFactory();
            case "AUTO"     -> new AutoLoanFactory();
            default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown loan type: " + loanType);
        };
    }
}
```

### Files affected

| Action | File |
|--------|------|
| **[NEW]** | `domain/controller/loan/LoanFactory.java` — abstract factory interface |
| **[NEW]** | `domain/controller/loan/LoanValidator.java` — validator interface |
| **[NEW]** | `domain/controller/loan/LoanInterestCalculator.java` — interest calculator interface |
| **[NEW]** | `domain/controller/loan/PersonalLoanFactory.java` — concrete factory |
| **[NEW]** | `domain/controller/loan/HomeLoanFactory.java` — concrete factory |
| **[NEW]** | `domain/controller/loan/AutoLoanFactory.java` — concrete factory |
| **[MODIFY]** | [domain/controller/LoanApplicationHandler.java](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/LoanApplicationHandler.java) — use `LoanFactory` |
| **[MODIFY]** | [domain/controller/LoanDecisionHandler.java](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/LoanDecisionHandler.java) — use `LoanFactory` for recalculation |
| **[MODIFY]** | [domain/entity/Loan.java](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Loan.java) — add `interestRate` field |

